  static Map<String, KemeticDayInfo> _buildHathorIIEntries() {
    const month = 'Hathor (Tepy-a Kenmet)';
    return _buildGeneratedDecanEntries(
      keyPrefix: 'hathor',
      decan: 2,
      decanLabel: 'Hathor II',
      monthLabelForDate: 'Hathor',
      month: month,
      flowRows: hathorIIFlowRows,
      entries: [
        (
          totalDay: 11,
          starCluster:
              '✨ The companion star rises just behind the lead light, like a loyal twin. Priests tracked night timing by watching the pair move together.',
          maatPrinciple: 'Name the Partnership',
          cosmicContext: '''
The first Hathor decan was you returning to your body, your home, your worth.
The second decan says: now return to your people.
ḥry-ib sꜣḥ is not a solitary star-image. It is companionship: one light moving with another, not in confusion, not in rivalry, not in collapse.
Day 11 is the speaking of “we.”
Not vague “us,” not emotional blur, not secret dependency disguised as love.
Specific bond. Specific labor. Specific alignment.
In Kemet, this is the kind of moment when crews, households, and work-pairs would be named in function after flood strain: who is rebuilding, who is restoring, who is carrying which part of the return.
A partnership becomes stronger when it is spoken clearly enough to be lived.
''',
          glyph:
              'shared standard 𓌡 above two linked figures — one purpose, two carriers',
          colorFrequency: 'Twin golds merging into one line of light',
          mantra: '"Our bond serves Ma’at."',
        ),
        (
          totalDay: 12,
          starCluster:
              '✨ The paired stars hold their night-course by timing, not by guessing',
          maatPrinciple: 'Sync the Rhythm',
          cosmicContext: '''
After a bond is named, the next truth is rhythm.
Two people can love each other and still grind each other down if their pace is unspoken.
ḥry-ib sꜣḥ is not just about closeness; it is about coordinated movement.
The decans themselves were read through timing and sequence. Their value was not simply that they appeared, but that they appeared in order.
Day 12 is that principle brought into daily life.
When do we move? When do we rest? When do we check in? Who starts early? Who takes late watch?
In Kemet, uncoordinated labor wasted strength. Timed labor preserved it.
Today is not romance alone. It is tempo.
And tempo is mercy when more than one life is involved.
''',
          glyph:
              'metronomic drum / clapper + two feet in stride — shared tempo',
          colorFrequency:
              'Warm gold pulsing over deep river blue — steady beat over flowing water',
          mantra: '"We set our pace together."',
        ),
        (
          totalDay: 13,
          starCluster:
              '✨ The “companion” aspect was not just romance. Crews in the fields, boat teams, grinding teams, canal maintenance teams — all moved in pairs or clusters.',
          maatPrinciple: 'Share the Load Fairly',
          cosmicContext: '''
Day 13 is redistribution.
Who is quietly doing 80% of the house work / money work / emotional work / parenting work / clean-up work / damage control work — and pretending they’re fine?
In Hathor’s logic, love is not “I’ll kill myself so you can rest.”
Love is “We carry this in a way that doesn’t break either one of us.”
ḥry-ib sꜣḥ is partnership as structure, not just as feeling.
In Kemet, paired work was not sentimental. It was survival intelligence. When labor was shared with honesty, households kept standing.
Today asks whether your care has become imbalance disguised as devotion.
If so, Ma’at requires correction before affection turns into quiet exploitation.
''',
          glyph: 'two shoulders under one carrying pole',
          colorFrequency: 'Copper-gold and deep blue',
          mantra: '"Love does not require silent overburden."',
        ),
        (
          totalDay: 14,
          starCluster:
              '✨ Companion-stars do not merge into one blur; each keeps its place while traveling beside the other',
          maatPrinciple: 'Keep Honesty in Friction',
          cosmicContext: '''
Partnership without truth becomes theater.
Truth without tenderness becomes poison.
Day 14 is the discipline of clean friction.
ḥry-ib sꜣḥ teaches that walking beside someone does not mean swallowing everything, nor does it mean using conflict to dominate them.
The two lights stay distinct. That distinction is part of what makes the pairing stable.
In Kemetic order, speech matters because words shape relation.
So when something is off, say it early. Say it clearly. Say it without rot.
This day is not about winning. It is about keeping the bond from decaying under unsaid resentment or theatrical silence.
The earlier the correction, the cleaner the repair.
''',
          glyph:
              '𓂋 between two figures — truth placed between us, not used against us',
          colorFrequency:
              'Gold line between two bodies, linking rather than cutting',
          mantra: '"We speak truth to heal, not to win."',
        ),
        (
          totalDay: 15,
          starCluster:
              '✨ This pair-star guided night labor on canals and grain storage. This day is infrastructure day.',
          maatPrinciple: 'Repair the Commons',
          cosmicContext: '''
Day 15 is where you fix the actual shared system.
Not theory. Actual fix.
That could be: how food gets handled, how money moves, how kid schedule works, how the workspace is set, how chores are divided, how you’re tracking time.
Kemet knew: if the canal wall breaks, it floods both houses.
So you fix the canal wall together.
ḥry-ib sꜣḥ is partnership moving from emotion into architecture.
Not “do we care?” but “what holds us?”
Today says that shared peace is built through repaired systems, not hopeful talk alone.
''',
          glyph:
              'canal wall 𓈗 + repair hand 𓂧 — “we shore up what protects both of us”',
          colorFrequency:
              'Mud brown reinforced with steady gold — stability as love',
          mantra: '"We fix the system, not each other."',
        ),
        (
          totalDay: 16,
          starCluster:
              '✨ The paired decan is described as traveling “with” — not in front of, not behind, but beside. This is protection energy.',
          maatPrinciple: 'Pledge Mutual Protection',
          cosmicContext: '''
Day 16 is mutual protection.
You say out loud:
“When you’re not in the room, I hold you up, not tear you down.”
That is sacred. That’s Hathor loyalty.
Protection is Ma’at because it preserves dignity, and dignity preserves stability.
Kemet understood reputation as infrastructure.
If somebody slanders you, that can cost food, alliance, trust, and continuity.
ḥry-ib sꜣḥ is not only shared labor. It is shared covering.
Today asks whether your bond has defensive strength: whether each person’s name remains clean in the other’s keeping.
''',
          glyph:
              'protective arm curved around another figure under a shared standard',
          colorFrequency: 'Deep indigo and protective gold',
          mantra: '"I hold your name clean."',
        ),
        (
          totalDay: 17,
          starCluster:
              '✨ The paired decan was celebrated as loyal and faithful. Companionship itself had sacred status.',
          maatPrinciple: 'Honor the Work Done Together',
          cosmicContext: '''
Day 17 is recognition.
Not “Look what I did.”
“We did that.”
Give actual praise for shared wins — money stabilized, kids fed, crisis handled, canal patched, house cleaned, account protected, peace kept.
Kemet made music in the fields during work for a reason.
Celebration wasn’t extra.
It bonded crews so they’d keep showing up.
ḥry-ib sꜣḥ here becomes visible joy in cooperation.
Praise is maintenance.
When shared work is named, people keep wanting to belong to it.
''',
          glyph: 'two linked figures beneath a lifted standard',
          colorFrequency: 'Twin golds over one dark line',
          mantra: '"We name what we built together."',
        ),
        (
          totalDay: 18,
          starCluster:
              '✨ The pair keeps moving because its pattern is adjusted, not frozen',
          maatPrinciple: 'Refine the System Together',
          cosmicContext: '''
A shared system that helped once may still need refinement.
Hathor is not softness without intelligence.
ḥry-ib sꜣḥ also teaches adaptation: two moving lights remain paired because their relation keeps holding, not because they never need adjustment.
Day 18 is for tuning.
How do we make this smoother for both of us, not just efficient for one of us?
Which step is clumsy? Which duty is misplaced? Which expectation needs changing?
In Kemet, systems that fed life were maintained through observation and correction, not blind repetition.
Today honors the partnership by making it more livable.
''',
          glyph: 'paired feet corrected into one shared line',
          colorFrequency: 'Gold pulse over deep river blue',
          mantra: '"We refine what we intend to keep."',
        ),
        (
          totalDay: 19,
          starCluster: '✨ Twin lights resting in one field of night',
          maatPrinciple: 'Rest in Harmony',
          cosmicContext: '''
Not all shared time should be labor.
Not all peace should be earned through exhaustion first.
Day 19 is a corrective to utilitarian bonding.
ḥry-ib sꜣḥ asks whether two people can inhabit the same room in calm without performing usefulness for each other.
Shared stillness is not laziness.
It is proof that the bond is not held together only by work output, crisis response, or mutual obligation.
In Kemet, rhythm always included pause. Music included silence. Night watch included the measured space between signals.
Today is for peace in company.
Can we be quiet together and still feel joined?
''',
          glyph: 'two seated figures beneath one calm line',
          colorFrequency: 'Soft gold and night blue',
          mantra: '"We are allowed peace together."',
        ),
        (
          totalDay: 20,
          starCluster:
              '✨ The companion-star remains beside the foremost — bond held in visible order',
          maatPrinciple: 'Reaffirm the Bond to Ma’at',
          cosmicContext: '''
The second Hathor decan closes by naming the bond itself as part of balance.
Not an accident.
Not just chemistry.
Not only convenience.
ḥry-ib sꜣḥ shows that companionship can be structurally sacred when it is honest, reciprocal, protective, and rhythmically kept.
Day 20 is not sentimentality. It is recognition.
You say: this bond has become part of how Ma’at is maintained in my life.
That does not make it perfect.
It makes it witnessed.
And what is witnessed can be tended with more seriousness than what is left vague.
Close the decan with gratitude for the partnership itself — the shared standard, the cleaned speech, the repaired commons, the defended dignity, the rested peace.
''',
          glyph:
              'shared standard 𓌡 above two linked figures — one purpose, two carriers',
          colorFrequency: 'Twin golds merging into one line of light',
          mantra: '"Our bond serves Ma’at."',
        ),
      ],
    );
  }

  static Map<String, KemeticDayInfo> _buildHathorIIIEntries() {
    const month = 'Hathor (Ḥwt-Ḥr)';
    return _buildGeneratedDecanEntries(
      keyPrefix: 'hathor',
      decan: 3,
      decanLabel: 'Hathor III',
      monthLabelForDate: 'Hathor',
      month: month,
      flowRows: hathorIIIFlowRows,
      entries: [
        (
          totalDay: 21,
          starCluster:
              '✨ Sah (Orion) made radiant — the restored body no longer hidden, but visibly ordered',
          maatPrinciple: 'Reveal the Restored Self',
          cosmicContext: '''
The first two Hathor decans brought you back into the body, the home, and the bond.
This third decan asks a harder question: now that you have been restored, will you let that restoration be seen?
The name sbꜣ sꜣḥ joins star-light with Sah, the celestial form tied to Asar in the older Kemetic funerary imagination.
Sah is not raw wound. Sah is the body reassembled and set in the sky as pattern.
That matters here. Hathor III is not about private healing alone. It is about ordered visibility.
In Kemetic thought, beauty is not separate from truth. What is rightly restored can become radiant without becoming false.
Day 21 is therefore not vanity and not concealment. It is presentation after repair.
You ask whether your life is ready to appear in form — not because it is perfect, but because it is no longer collapsing.
''',
          glyph:
              'star set above the upright Sah-body — beauty established in order',
          colorFrequency: 'Lapis blue, polished gold, and soft ivory',
          mantra: '"What is restored in me may now be seen."',
        ),
        (
          totalDay: 22,
          starCluster:
              '✨ A brightened Sah-form whose outline is now legible against the dark',
          maatPrinciple: 'Polish the Image',
          cosmicContext: '''
Once something has been restored, the next labor is refinement.
Not falsification. Not vanity. Refinement.
Kemetic sacred culture put enormous care into visible form: garments, paint, vessels, architecture, carved names, polished stone, perfumed space.
This was not empty luxury. It was a declaration that what matters should appear in a way worthy of its function.
Day 22 applies that principle to the self and its visible field.
If a room, body, entrance, altar, or public representation carries your name, then bringing it into better form is not superficial. It is alignment.
You are not polishing emptiness. You are letting outer presentation catch up to inner repair.
''',
          glyph: 'polished mirror disk under a star',
          colorFrequency: 'ivory-white, gold, and blue-black',
          mantra: '"I refine what carries my name."',
        ),
        (
          totalDay: 23,
          starCluster:
              '✨ star-form and body-form matching one another instead of competing',
          maatPrinciple: 'Let Beauty Tell the Truth',
          cosmicContext: '''
This day rejects two opposites: ugliness worn like virtue and beauty used like a mask.
Hathor belongs to beauty, but in Kemetic sacred logic beauty is strongest when it reveals order rather than covering disorder.
Sah adds another layer: the body as constellation, a pattern that can be recognized because it has coherence.
So Day 23 asks for adornment that tells the truth.
Music that actually softens and steadies. Clothing that reflects dignity instead of insecurity. Fragrance that marks reverence instead of performance.
The question is not “How do I look impressive?”
The question is “What form best reveals the state I have actually earned?”
''',
          glyph: 'lotus before the open eye',
          colorFrequency: 'lotus blue, warm rose-gold, and soft black',
          mantra: '"My beauty is truest when it is honest."',
        ),
        (
          totalDay: 24,
          starCluster:
              '✨ a constellation is not only seen — it is read, named, and responded to',
          maatPrinciple: 'Speak From Restored Ground',
          cosmicContext: '''
One of the clearest signs of restoration is the voice.
Not loudness. Not eloquence. Ground.
In the older Kemetic materials, speech is never trivial. It creates, affirms, protects, judges, praises, and restores relation.
Day 24 therefore moves from visible form to audible form.
What do you sound like now that you are not only surviving?
Do you still speak from flinch, defense, panic, or shame?
Or has the body’s return begun to change the mouth as well?
This day favors saying one true thing from calm.
A boundary. A blessing. A plan. A need. A thanks.
When the voice comes from restored ground, it carries less poison and more force.
''',
          glyph: 'mouth-sign beneath a star',
          colorFrequency: 'gold line over still blue-black',
          mantra: '"My voice comes from steadied ground."',
        ),
        (
          totalDay: 25,
          starCluster:
              '✨ the star does not chase the eye; it shines and is found',
          maatPrinciple: 'Radiate Without Chasing',
          cosmicContext: '''
This is one of the most difficult Hathor teachings: luminosity without grasping.
There is a difference between becoming visible and begging to be chosen.
The first belongs to restored order. The second usually belongs to hunger and injury.
Day 25 asks whether you can let beauty, worth, and readiness be seen without over-speaking, over-offering, or collapsing your center for approval.
Sah’s stellar form helps here. A constellation does not chase. It appears, holds, and is recognized by those with eyes to read it.
This day is not withdrawal. It is non-desperate presence.
Magnetism held inside dignity.
''',
          glyph: 'steady star above a still face',
          colorFrequency: 'bright gold and midnight blue',
          mantra: '"I do not chase what can already see me."',
        ),
        (
          totalDay: 26,
          starCluster:
              '✨ warm star-light meeting the body without dissolving its outline',
          maatPrinciple: 'Align Love and Radiance',
          cosmicContext: '''
This day brings a useful tension into view: how do warmth, attraction, affection, softness, and beauty move through relationship without blurring structure?
Hathor is often misread as sweetness without boundaries. Kemetic sources do not support that simplification.
She is joy, yes — but also presence, force, music, intoxication held in cultic order, and beauty with divine gravity.
Day 26 therefore asks for relational radiance with clarity.
Can you be open without becoming vague? Warm without becoming available to everything? Magnetic without abandoning discernment?
Sah’s star-form helps again: beauty with outline.
This day is strongest when affection does not make you less exact, but more alive and more clearly placed.
''',
          glyph: 'lotus stem held upright in two balanced hands',
          colorFrequency: 'lotus blue, rose-gold, and black',
          mantra: '"My openness keeps its shape."',
        ),
        (
          totalDay: 27,
          starCluster:
              '✨ the body as constellation, the constellation as body — care made visible',
          maatPrinciple: 'Honor the Sacred Body',
          cosmicContext: '''
Today returns directly to one of the oldest Kemetic insights in your source base: the body can be read cosmically.
Sah is not merely a group of stars; it is the celestialized body of Asar in older mortuary imagination, the reassembled form that continues above.
That matters because it means bodily form is not low or disposable. It can carry divine pattern.
Hathor III therefore makes body-tending into theology.
Bathing, oiling, stretching, dressing, resting, scenting, ornamenting — these are not trivial acts when done in order.
They say: this vessel is worth maintaining because spirit lives through it.
Day 27 is not punishment-fitness. It is reverent care for the house through which your visible life appears.
''',
          glyph: 'Sah-body outlined in stars above anointed shoulders',
          colorFrequency: 'warm oil-gold over night blue',
          mantra: '"My body deserves beautiful maintenance."',
        ),
        (
          totalDay: 28,
          starCluster:
              '✨ the room taking on the order of the star-body that enters it',
          maatPrinciple: 'Bless the Room',
          cosmicContext: '''
Kemetic sacred life rarely isolates the self from the field around it.
A room can become thick with disorder, harshness, neglect, or emotional spill. It can also be lifted.
Day 28 asks whether your presence changes atmosphere toward life.
Not by domination. By refinement.
Light adjusted. Fragrance added. Noise lowered. Beauty introduced. Harshness softened. Disorder cleaned.
Hathor’s force often enters through environment — music, festival, scent, ornament, hospitality, delight — while Sah contributes ordered placement.
Together they give a simple test: when you enter, does the room become more breathable, more beautiful, more balanced, more human?
If so, your presence is not just visible. It is beneficial.
''',
          glyph: 'lamp, lotus, and ordered threshold',
          colorFrequency: 'amber-gold, lotus blue, and matte black',
          mantra: '"My presence sweetens the field."',
        ),
        (
          totalDay: 29,
          starCluster:
              '✨ a star that holds brightness by staying in pattern, not by flaring wildly',
          maatPrinciple: 'Hold Beauty Steady',
          cosmicContext: '''
The danger at the end of a radiance cycle is excess.
Once beauty returns, it can tip into performance. Once confidence returns, it can spill into hunger. Once openness returns, it can dissolve boundaries.
Day 29 is therefore not a dimming day, but a steadying day.
The question is whether your radiance can remain ordered.
Can beauty stay linked to Ma’at instead of running into vanity, emotional leakage, overexposure, or the need to constantly prove itself?
Sah’s pattern helps again: its recognizability depends on structure. Hathor’s sweetness becomes most powerful when it is held inside form.
This day asks for luminous stability rather than unstable intensity.
''',
          glyph: 'steady star over balanced scales',
          colorFrequency: 'bright gold, indigo, and white',
          mantra: '"My radiance stays in order."',
        ),
        (
          totalDay: 30,
          starCluster:
              '✨ Sah in full star-form — reassembled, visible, named, and held in the heavens',
          maatPrinciple: 'Seal the Star-Form',
          cosmicContext: '''
Hathor closes with revelation held in order.
Across the month, you returned to body, house, bond, joy, dignity, and visible form.
Now the question is not whether something in you has changed. It is whether that change has become stable enough to name.
The phrase sbꜣ sꜣḥ is powerful here because it lets the month end not merely in softness, but in stellar coherence: beauty joined to a body that has been repaired and placed in visible order.
That is more than confidence. It is form.
This final day asks you to mark what has become true enough to carry forward — what now shines in you because it is no longer scattered, hidden, starved, or collapsing.
Seal it. Name it. Keep it.
Do not rush past this.
A star-form is not built in one flash. It is earned through repeated restoration until radiance becomes structurally believable.
''',
          glyph: 'star placed above the upright Sah-body',
          colorFrequency: 'luminous gold, lapis blue, and soft white',
          mantra: '"What has been restored in me now shines in order."',
        ),
      ],
    );
  }

  static Map<String, KemeticDayInfo> _buildKaHerKaIEntries() {
    const month = 'Ka-her-Ka (Kꜣ-ḥr-Kꜣ)';
    return _buildGeneratedDecanEntries(
      keyPrefix: 'kaherka',
      decan: 1,
      decanLabel: 'Ka-her-Ka I',
      monthLabelForDate: 'Ka-her-Ka',
      month: month,
      flowRows: kaHerKaIFlowRows,
      entries: [
        (
          totalDay: 1,
          starCluster:
              '✨ msḥtjw — the binding stars, a pattern of fastening, joining, and secured continuity',
          maatPrinciple: 'Bind What Must Hold',
          cosmicContext: '''
After Hathor’s restoration and visible beauty, Ka-her-Ka begins with fastening.
This is the month where what has been healed must now be secured.
The image behind msḥtjw is not loose inspiration. It is binding, lashing, tightening, making something hold under strain.
Day 1 is therefore not about starting from zero. It is about deciding what in your life is now worthy of being firmly tied into place.
What should remain? What should be fixed so it does not drift back into disorder?
This is the first day of commitment becoming structure.
''',
          glyph: 'tied cord over a stable base',
          colorFrequency: 'deep blue-black and binding gold',
          mantra: '"What matters now holds."',
        ),
        (
          totalDay: 2,
          starCluster:
              '✨ the first lashings taking shape — order no longer imagined, but attached',
          maatPrinciple: 'Tighten the First Knot',
          cosmicContext: '''
A thing is not secured because you feel serious about it.
It is secured when the first knot is tied.
Ka-her-Ka begins by moving from admiration to fastening, from intention to mechanism.
Day 2 asks for one practical act that makes drift harder.
A rule. A place. A container. A schedule. A repeated time.
This is the day where the abstract promise first becomes difficult to ignore.
''',
          glyph: 'first knot tied into cord',
          colorFrequency: 'bronze-gold and dark indigo',
          mantra: '"I make drift less possible."',
        ),
        (
          totalDay: 3,
          starCluster: '✨ a bound structure inspected at its edges',
          maatPrinciple: 'Secure the Weak Edge',
          cosmicContext: '''
Most things do not fail in the center first.
They fail at the seam, the overlooked edge, the unguarded joint.
So Day 3 is inspection.
Where is the weak point in the bond, schedule, room, promise, or system you are trying to keep?
The work here is not dramatic. It is precise.
You strengthen the place most likely to loosen before it becomes the point of collapse.
''',
          glyph: 'reinforced seam with tied cord',
          colorFrequency: 'dark clay and gold',
          mantra: '"I strengthen the place most likely to fail."',
        ),
        (
          totalDay: 4,
          starCluster: '✨ a fastened form under real strain',
          maatPrinciple: 'Test the Binding',
          cosmicContext: '''
A thing is not secure because it looks secure.
It is secure when it continues under pressure.
Day 4 asks you to use the system, live the rule, walk the schedule, lean on the bond, and see what actually holds.
Testing is not distrust. It is respect for reality.
What proves itself under friction becomes worthy of deeper trust.
''',
          glyph: 'weighted cord across stable posts',
          colorFrequency: 'iron-gold and indigo',
          mantra: '"What holds under pressure is worth trusting."',
        ),
        (
          totalDay: 5,
          starCluster: '✨ binding done in proportion, not panic',
          maatPrinciple: 'Bind in Order, Not Fear',
          cosmicContext: '''
There is a holy tightening and an anxious tightening.
One preserves life. The other crushes it.
Day 5 asks whether your fastening is done in Ma’at or in fear.
Are you creating structure, or overcorrecting into control?
Secure things, yes. But do not strangle them trying to prevent every possible future uncertainty.
Balance is part of the binding.
''',
          glyph: 'balanced knot over scales',
          colorFrequency: 'gold, black, and muted blue',
          mantra: '"I secure without suffocating."',
        ),
        (
          totalDay: 6,
          starCluster:
              '✨ inner force and outer framework brought into one line',
          maatPrinciple: 'Pair the Inner and Outer',
          cosmicContext: '''
A vow inside the heart and a system outside the body should not be strangers to one another.
Day 6 asks whether the thing you say matters is actually reflected in the way your life is arranged.
If not, the outer frame will slowly betray the inner claim.
This is the day of matching declaration with design.
A fastened life feels less divided when the inside and outside stop contradicting each other.
''',
          glyph: 'heart joined to a tied cord',
          colorFrequency: 'dark red-gold and deep blue',
          mantra: '"My structure reflects my true vow."',
        ),
        (
          totalDay: 7,
          starCluster: '✨ the fastening tools laid out in proper order',
          maatPrinciple: 'Respect the Fastening Tools',
          cosmicContext: '''
Nothing holds itself.
There are always tools, supports, rules, helpers, containers, and repeated acts doing the quiet work of preservation.
Day 7 is for respecting them.
The cord, the storage bin, the written rule, the schedule, the reminder, the shared agreement, the kept place — these are not boring details. They are the instruments of continuity.
Today asks for care toward what is doing the holding.
''',
          glyph: 'neatly laid tools beside tied cord',
          colorFrequency: 'bronze, gold, and clay-black',
          mantra: '"I honor what quietly keeps things together."',
        ),
        (
          totalDay: 8,
          starCluster:
              '✨ tension held in correct measure so the structure remains alive',
          maatPrinciple: 'Keep Tension Balanced',
          cosmicContext: '''
A structure fails when it is too loose.
It also fails when it is too tight.
So Day 8 is adjustment.
You look for the places where more discipline is needed and the places where more give is needed.
This is not inconsistency. It is proportion.
What is bound in Ma’at stays usable because it is held in living balance, not dead rigidity.
''',
          glyph: 'balanced cord between two fixed points',
          colorFrequency: 'gold, deep blue, and soft gray',
          mantra: '"I hold with proportion."',
        ),
        (
          totalDay: 9,
          starCluster: '✨ the binding seen again in light of its purpose',
          maatPrinciple: 'Bind It to Purpose',
          cosmicContext: '''
Structure without purpose becomes mere habit.
Day 9 returns to the reason the binding exists at all.
Why is this worth holding?
What is it protecting? What does it preserve? What dignity, continuity, peace, or growth depends on it staying intact?
When structure is reconnected to purpose, it becomes easier to keep without resentment.
You remember not only the knot, but the life it serves.
''',
          glyph: 'tied cord linked to a stable house',
          colorFrequency: 'warm gold and fertile black',
          mantra: '"I remember what this structure protects."',
        ),
        (
          totalDay: 10,
          starCluster:
              '✨ the first binding complete — no longer loose possibility, but held form',
          maatPrinciple: 'Seal the First Binding',
          cosmicContext: '''
The first Ka-her-Ka decan closes with seal and acknowledgment.
Something that began as possibility has now been tied, tested, adjusted, and connected to purpose.
It is not finished forever, but it is no longer loose.
That matters.
Day 10 is for naming what now stands under your care with more firmness than it did ten days ago.
A first binding is sacred because it changes the future shape of drift.
What has been fastened becomes harder to lose.
''',
          glyph: 'sealed knot above a steady base',
          colorFrequency: 'gold, indigo, and black',
          mantra: '"What I have bound now stands."',
        ),
      ],
