  static Map<String, KemeticDayInfo> _buildShefBedetIIEntries() {
    const season = '🌿 Peret — Season of Emergence';
    const month = 'Šef-Bedet (Šf-bdt)';
    return _buildGeneratedDecanEntries(
      keyPrefix: 'sefbedet',
      decan: 2,
      decanLabel: 'Šef-Bedet II',
      monthLabelForDate: 'Šef-Bedet',
      month: month,
      season: season,
      flowRows: shefBedetIIFlowRows,
      entries: [
        (
          totalDay: 11,
          starCluster:
              '✨ A dim curve of stars arcing north, read as a coiled serpent. Farmers said Renenutet herself glided that curve at night, inspecting crops, driving off pests, and blessing the grain that would feed the village. Offerings of milk were poured at field corners: “Her drink is cool, so her judgment is calm.”',
          maatPrinciple: 'Walk the Boundary',
          cosmicContext: '''
Day 11 is patrol.
After the clay is shaped and the shoots are up, the work shifts from forming to guarding. The ancients walked the edges of their plots at dawn and dusk, scanning for burrows, tracks, chew marks, fungus, theft. That walk was not paranoia. It was love.
Today you walk your own perimeter — money, body, time, home, children, peace. You look honestly at where chaos is slipping in: late-night scrolling that wrecks your sleep, a person who only calls when they are hungry, a leak in your spending, a stress spiral that is already drying you out.
Renenutet’s gaze was considered mercy because it caught the threat early. You do the same. You do not look away.
''',
          glyph:
              'Four small offering bowls at the four corners of a planted square',
          colorFrequency: 'Milk white cooling over fertile green',
          mantra: 'I maintain the guard that maintains me.',
        ),
        (
          totalDay: 12,
          starCluster:
              '✨ The serpent arc was not fear imagery. It was precision. Renenutet, “She Who Reaps in Her Season,” was honored for identifying anything that would cost the people their stored future. Priests said: “Her eyes drive harm into the sand.”',
          maatPrinciple: 'Name the Pest',
          cosmicContext: '''
Day 12 is honesty.
In Kemet, you did not pretend rats were “not that bad.” You named them. You trapped them. You sealed the grain.
Today you stop romanticizing the thing that is draining you. You say its name — the habit that is bleeding money, the person who escalates drama then says it is love, the excuse that keeps you tired, the food that keeps you inflamed and fogged, the self-story that keeps you small.
You do not have to fix it all in one motion. But you must stop lying about it.
Ma’at cannot operate where denial is being worshiped.
''',
          glyph: 'Striking cobra over fallen vermin',
          colorFrequency:
              'Sunlit gold at the hood edge, blacked-out shadow beneath',
          mantra: 'I remove what endangers my future.',
        ),
        (
          totalDay: 13,
          starCluster:
              '✨ The serpent’s work was not just to strike but to encircle, cool, and guard. Offerings at the field corners marked the perimeter as watched.',
          maatPrinciple: 'Lay Protective Offerings',
          cosmicContext: '''
Day 13 is reinforcement before disaster.
Protection in Kemet was not treated as panic. It was ordinary wisdom. Locks, stored food, sealed jars, shaded growth, watched entrances — all of it said the same thing: what feeds life deserves guarding.
Today you strengthen the guard deliberately: rituals, nutrition, sleep, locks, agreements, budgeting, passwords, boundaries, routines.
The goal is not fear. The goal is waking safer tomorrow than you were today.
''',
          glyph:
              'Four small offering bowls at the four corners of a planted square',
          colorFrequency: 'Milk white cooling over fertile green',
          mantra: 'I maintain the guard that maintains me.',
        ),
        (
          totalDay: 14,
          starCluster:
              '✨ Renenutet was invoked both as feeder and as striker. Her cobra hood was the promise that anything threatening the stored grain would be met without hesitation.',
          maatPrinciple: 'Strike the Threat',
          cosmicContext: '''
Day 14 is decisive removal.
There is a point where guarding is not enough. You do not negotiate with the rat inside the grain bin. You remove it.
This is the day of cutting access, saying no, blocking, ending the leak, driving the threat out of the field.
Mercy is not permissiveness when life is being eaten.
What harms growth must lose its proximity.
''',
          glyph: 'Striking cobra over fallen vermin',
          colorFrequency:
              'Sunlit gold at the hood edge, blacked-out shadow beneath',
          mantra: 'I remove what endangers my future.',
        ),
        (
          totalDay: 15,
          starCluster:
              '✨ Renenutet’s presence was also cooling. “Her breath makes the green live,” said the hymn. Overheating — conflict, drought, fever — could kill a crop faster than insects.',
          maatPrinciple: 'Cool the Field',
          cosmicContext: '''
Day 15 is heat management.
Too much sun scorches sprouts. Too much anger scorches relationships. Too much adrenaline scorches the body.
Cooling the field is not apathy. It is intelligent regulation.
Today you deliberately lower destructive heat. You de-escalate a fight before it becomes scorched earth. You reduce input that overstimulates you. You ice inflammation. You step back from the argument that will cost you sleep and money.
In Kemet they shaded the most tender growth. You shade what is tender in you and around you.
Your calm is not surrender. Your calm is preservation.
''',
          glyph: 'Curled serpent exhaling cool breath across young shoots',
          colorFrequency: 'Pale blue-green over sun-warmed earth',
          mantra: 'I lower the heat so life can keep growing.',
        ),
        (
          totalDay: 16,
          starCluster:
              '✨ Renenutet was also the goddess of the granary. Once something was harvested or saved, guarding it was holy. Theft from the storehouse was not just crime — it was assault on next season’s children.',
          maatPrinciple: 'Guard the Storehouse',
          cosmicContext: '''
Day 16 is defense of what you already secured.
This is not the day to admire the saved grain and assume that is enough.
You protect stored value: food, money, saved energy, repaired trust.
What has been gathered must now be watched.
Future life depends on present guarding.
''',
          glyph: 'Coiled cobra encircling a bundle of grain',
          colorFrequency: 'Guarding bronze around ripening green',
          mantra: 'I see what approaches my field.',
        ),
        (
          totalDay: 17,
          starCluster:
              '✨ The guard tightens its living ring — access becomes intentional, not assumed.',
          maatPrinciple: 'Tighten the Circle',
          cosmicContext: '''
Day 17 is access control.
After boundary, naming, protection, and storage, the next question is simple: who is inside the circle and who is not?
This is not cruelty. It is stewardship.
What feeds life cannot remain open to everything.
The circle should be tight enough to preserve peace and loose enough to keep life breathing.
''',
          glyph: 'Raised cobra beside a carved oath-staff',
          colorFrequency: 'Statement gold on disciplined dark brown',
          mantra: 'My law is spoken and will be honored.',
        ),
        (
          totalDay: 18,
          starCluster:
              '✨ The serpent’s eyes stay open long enough to notice what was lost, not only what was saved.',
          maatPrinciple: 'Track the Losses',
          cosmicContext: '''
Day 18 is accounting without denial.
Where did life escape your hands?
Leaks, waste, theft, relapse, erosion — the point is not shame. The point is truthful record.
Without that record, you cannot know what the field actually cost you.
Ma’at requires count, not theater.
''',
          glyph: 'scribe marks beside a breached store-jar',
          colorFrequency: 'ink black and grain gold',
          mantra: 'I record what escaped, so I can keep better.',
        ),
        (
          totalDay: 19,
          starCluster:
              '✨ The guarded field remains safe because its law is spoken aloud and remembered.',
          maatPrinciple: 'Reinforce the Oath',
          cosmicContext: '''
Day 19 is spoken law.
Protection cannot stay vague.
You restate your terms: how you will be treated, how resources will be handled, how peace is kept.
The oath matters because what is unspoken is easier to betray.
This is the day the field hears its law again.
''',
          glyph: 'Raised cobra beside a carved oath-staff',
          colorFrequency: 'Statement gold on disciplined dark brown',
          mantra: 'My law is spoken and will be honored.',
        ),
        (
          totalDay: 20,
          starCluster:
              '✨ As this serpent arc declined from the night sky, the teaching was: vigilance must become habit, not adrenaline. The field is not safe because you panicked once. It is safe because you stay awake.',
          maatPrinciple: 'Stand Watch at Dusk',
          cosmicContext: '''
Day 20 is quiet vigilance.
The end of this decan is not explosive. It is settled. Serpent-coiled. Eyes half-lidded but awake.
Tonight you sit with awareness. You slow your body, soften your jaw, and review the patterns you saw across these ten days: where did threats show up, where did you shut them down early, where did you wait too long, who proved trustworthy, who revealed themselves?
Renenutet inspects the fields at night. You inspect your life at night.
This is not anxiety. This is guardianship.
You tell the world, and yourself: “I am awake at my own border.”
''',
          glyph:
              'Four small offering bowls at the four corners of a planted square',
          colorFrequency: 'Milk white cooling over fertile green',
          mantra: 'I maintain the guard that maintains me.',
        ),
      ],
    );
  }

  static Map<String, KemeticDayInfo> _buildShefBedetIIIEntries() {
    const season = '🌿 Peret — Season of Emergence';
    const month = 'Šef-Bedet (Šf-bdt)';
    return _buildGeneratedDecanEntries(
      keyPrefix: 'sefbedet',
      decan: 3,
      decanLabel: 'Šef-Bedet III',
      monthLabelForDate: 'Šef-Bedet',
      month: month,
      season: season,
      flowRows: shefBedetIIIFlowRows,
      entries: [
        (
          totalDay: 21,
          starCluster:
              '✨ The forward-rising star now seen after the guarding work — not as alarm, but as steady orientation',
          maatPrinciple: 'Exhale the Tension',
          cosmicContext: '''
The first Šef-Bedet decan formed and fed the living field. The second guarded it. This third decan is not laziness and it is not collapse. It is the lawful easing that comes once nourishment has been planted, watched, and protected. In the older source base, nourishment, bread, grain, and sustenance are tied to continued life under Ma’at, not to permanent panic.
Day 21 therefore begins with unclenching. You are not asked to abandon the field. You are asked to stop living like danger is the only sacred posture. What has been protected should now be witnessed without fear.
''',
          glyph:
              'Long serpent in a loose ring, not constricting — simply present',
          colorFrequency: 'Calm olive and warm clay',
          mantra: 'I trust the order I built.',
        ),
        (
          totalDay: 22,
          starCluster: '✨ The field seen in first light after night watch',
          maatPrinciple: 'Acknowledge the Living Field',
          cosmicContext: '''
A guarded field must eventually be looked at without panic. The older nourishment texts are concerned not only with danger, but with abundance, bread, grain, and the continuance of life itself.
Today is for direct witness. Not fantasy, not minimization. You look at what survived because you kept tending it. That act matters because reality, not mood, is the ground of Ma’at.
''',
          glyph: 'Open eye over sprouted grain',
          colorFrequency: 'Living green and dark earth',
          mantra: 'I look directly at what lived.',
        ),
        (
          totalDay: 23,
          starCluster: '✨ The forward star now read as promise, not warning',
          maatPrinciple: 'Bless What Will Feed Others',
          cosmicContext: '''
Bread, grain, and nourishment in the source texts are never only private. They belong to continued life, offering, and shared sustenance.
So today is about consequence beyond the self. What you guarded was not only for you. It will feed children, household, future work, peace, rest, and memory. Blessing that truth keeps the month from collapsing into mere self-protection.
''',
          glyph: 'Offering hands beneath grain',
          colorFrequency: 'Grain-gold and warm green',
          mantra: 'What I kept alive will feed more than me.',
        ),
        (
          totalDay: 24,
          starCluster: '✨ The star at the fore no longer chased, only followed',
          maatPrinciple: 'Loosen Control Without Leaving Ma’at',
          cosmicContext: '''
Once a field is planted, fed, and guarded, there is a point where constant gripping becomes its own disorder. The Kemetic agricultural record is full of regulation and control of water, but always toward continued fertility, not endless panic.
Today asks for trust without negligence. You do not abandon the field. You stop strangling it. That distinction is the whole day. Order that cannot breathe is already beginning to die.
''',
          glyph: 'Open hand above a settled field',
          colorFrequency: 'Soft olive and clay',
          mantra: 'I release my grip, not my standards.',
        ),
        (
          totalDay: 25,
          starCluster:
              '✨ The field is alive because the vessel that carried it is still standing',
          maatPrinciple: 'Tend the Vessel',
          cosmicContext: '''
The same source base that values food, grain, and provision also treats the body and its support systems as part of continued life, not as disposable tools. Food and drink themselves carry ka.
So today turns back toward the carrier. Hands, feet, throat, joints, sleep, tools, voice, and nerves all matter. A cracked jar spills grain. A neglected body spills order. Care here is not indulgence. It is maintenance of the carrier of nourishment.
''',
          glyph: 'Jar being mended and re-oiled',
          colorFrequency: 'Warm clay and quiet gold',
          mantra: 'I maintain the vessel that carries life.',
        ),
        (
          totalDay: 26,
          starCluster: '✨ What rose at the fore now passes forward',
          maatPrinciple: 'Name the Inheritance',
          cosmicContext: '''
What is nourished is meant to continue. The Kemetic record is full of transmission: fathers to children, rulers to people, food to life, offering to continuity, memory to posterity. Even ka is transmitted.
So today asks what is actually being handed forward through you. Not fantasy legacy. Real inheritance: steadier money, safer habits, calmer speech, better records, fed bodies, cleaner rooms, wiser terms, protected peace. Name it so it can be carried on purpose.
''',
          glyph: 'Open hands passing grain forward',
          colorFrequency: 'Grain-gold and black earth',
          mantra: 'I know what is passing through me.',
        ),
        (
          totalDay: 27,
          starCluster: '✨ The watched field now capable of joy without waste',
          maatPrinciple: 'Let Joy Return Lawfully',
          cosmicContext: '''
There is a Kemetic difference between joy and waste. Sustenance is sacred, but so are festival, music, relief, and gratitude when held in measure. The point is not permanent severity. The point is life under Ma’at.
So today allows gladness, but lawful gladness. You do not scorch the field to celebrate saving it. You receive relief without undoing the work. Joy becomes fuel instead of leakage.
''',
          glyph: 'Lotus opening above stored grain',
          colorFrequency: 'Honey-gold and soft green',
          mantra: 'My joy does not undo my order.',
        ),
        (
          totalDay: 28,
          starCluster:
              '✨ Nourishment received consciously becomes part of ordered life',
          maatPrinciple: 'Eat and Receive With Presence',
          cosmicContext: '''
Food and drink in the older texts are not casual matter. They carry contentment, sustenance, even ka.
So today is about receiving what feeds you without haste, shame, numbness, or performance. Eat, rest, listen, receive care, receive enough. To take in nourishment consciously is part of emergence, not a distraction from it.
''',
          glyph: 'Bread and water before an open mouth',
          colorFrequency: 'Bread-gold and river teal',
          mantra: 'I receive what feeds me in peace.',
        ),
        (
          totalDay: 29,
          starCluster:
              '✨ The field no longer watched in fear, but trusted in order',
          maatPrinciple: 'Trust the Order You Built',
          cosmicContext: '''
The point of vessel, nourishment, boundary, and record is not endless surveillance. It is stable continuance. The hydraulic and agricultural systems of Kemet were built so fields could keep living through measured control, not permanent emergency.
Today asks whether you can trust what has proven itself. Not blindly. Not foolishly. But enough to stop circling it in fear. Order becomes mature when it can hold without constant panic-touching.
''',
          glyph: 'House/storehouse marked and sealed, in active use',
          colorFrequency: 'Warm clay and stored-grain gold',
          mantra: 'This isn’t theory anymore. This feeds me.',
        ),
        (
          totalDay: 30,
          starCluster:
              '✨ The forward star lowering toward the next phase — nourishment carried onward, not dropped',
          maatPrinciple: 'Prepare the Hand-Off',
          cosmicContext: '''
Šef-Bedet closes not in exhaustion but in transfer. What has been formed, fed, guarded, and steadied is now prepared for the next phase. That is consistent with the source tradition’s emphasis on sustenance, order, and continuity rather than theatrical ending.
So the last day is for clean passage. Record what matters. Bless what continues. Put things in order so the next cycle begins with dignity intact. The keeper’s work is not only to save life, but to hand it forward well.
''',
          glyph: 'Open hands passing grain and record forward',
          colorFrequency: 'Grain-gold, dark earth, and quiet green',
          mantra: 'I hand forward what I kept alive.',
        ),
      ],
    );
  }

