  static Map<String, KemeticDayInfo> _buildMesutRaIEntries() {
    const season = '☀️ Shemu – Season of Harvest';
    const month =
        'Mesut-Ra (Mswt-Rꜥ) — the month of births of Ra, where what has been carried, stored, ordered, and prepared now enters emergence, arrival, and first appearance in the light';
    return _buildGeneratedDecanEntries(
      keyPrefix: 'mswtRa',
      decan: 1,
      decanLabel: 'Mesut-Ra I',
      monthLabelForDate: 'Mesut-Ra',
      month: month,
      season: season,
      flowRows: mesutRaOverrideIFlowRows,
      entries: [
        (
          totalDay: 1,
          starCluster:
              '✨ msḥtjw ḥꜣt — the birthing powers at the front: forces of emergence, first opening, and what presses from hidden formation into visible life',
          maatPrinciple: 'Let what is ready begin to emerge',
          cosmicContext: '''
Mesut-Ra begins with emergence.
By this point in Shemu, much has already been cut, carried, ordered, stored, refined, and prepared. But preparation is not the final act. In Kemet, what was formed in hiddenness had to come forth in its time. The chamber was never the end of life. It was the place from which life could emerge correctly.
That is the law of msḥtjw ḥꜣt.
This decan belongs to first appearance. Not random exposure. Not premature unveiling. Birth in the proper sense: what has been ripening beneath the surface now pressing into visibility because the time has become right.
So Day 1 is about honest emergence.
What in your life is no longer meant to remain latent? A work becoming public. A new role taking form. A discipline becoming daily reality. A truth that must now be spoken. A strength that can no longer stay hidden in preparation.
Birth is not fantasy. It is transition from inward formation into outward life.
''',
          glyph: 'Opening gate with the first light pressing through',
          colorFrequency: 'Dawn gold, red earth, and deep birthing blue',
          mantra: 'What is ready in truth, I allow to enter life.',
        ),
        (
          totalDay: 2,
          starCluster:
              '✨ msḥtjw ḥꜣt — first emergence under guarding hands, where what is newly born must not be left exposed too early',
          maatPrinciple: 'Guard the first opening',
          cosmicContext: '''
What has just emerged is real, but it is not yet hardened.
In Kemet, first appearance did not mean immediate exposure to every demand. What was new needed correct handling. The first shoot, the first cry, the first appearance of a form in light — all required protection while strength was still gathering itself.
Day 2 belongs to that guard.
You identify what could injure this beginning before it has learned to stand. Too many eyes. Too much explanation. Too much pressure. Too much comparison. Too much demand for proof. Too much of the old atmosphere surrounding what is trying to become new.
Early protection is not fear.
It is respect for the real vulnerability of beginnings.
''',
          glyph: 'New flame cupped by both hands',
          colorFrequency: 'Soft gold, guarded red, and shadow blue',
          mantra: 'I protect what is new until it can stand.',
        ),
        (
          totalDay: 3,
          starCluster:
              '✨ msḥtjw ḥꜣt — the birth-forces requiring clear speech, where what is emerging must be named if it is to gather form',
          maatPrinciple: 'Name the birth clearly',
          cosmicContext: '''
What is not named clearly is easily mishandled.
In Kemet, naming brought definition. It drew a line around the thing and distinguished it from the blur around it. Birth without naming remained uncertain. Something could be happening and still fail to gather force because no one had spoken plainly what it was.
Day 3 is definition.
You say what is being born. Not in swollen language. Not in vague aspiration. Plainly. A healthier body. A cleaner discipline. A finished work. A more ordered household. A restored standard. A new season of speech. A new role in service.
The new thing needs a true name so your labor can answer it correctly.
What is named rightly becomes easier to nourish, protect, and build.
''',
          glyph: 'Spoken name before the rising disk',
          colorFrequency: 'Ink black, sun gold, and clarified red',
          mantra: 'I name what is emerging so it can take form.',
        ),
        (
          totalDay: 4,
          starCluster:
              '✨ msḥtjw ḥꜣt — first emergence taking body, where a beginning must pass from concept into matter',
          maatPrinciple: 'Give the birth a body',
          cosmicContext: '''
A birth becomes real when it enters matter.
In Kemet, emergence was not complete because it was felt inwardly or envisioned correctly. It had to take body. A room prepared. A document made. A system begun. A rite enacted. A vessel filled. A path walked. Something visible had to now carry what was emerging.
Day 4 is incarnation.
You take one act that gives the new thing form. Open the account. Write the page. Begin the routine. Rearrange the room. Make the appointment. Build the file. Start the protocol. Put the body into the new agreement.
What is born must touch the ground.
Otherwise it remains a possibility mistaken for a life.
''',
          glyph: 'First form rising from the birthing ground',
          colorFrequency: 'Earth red, morning gold, and active blue',
          mantra: 'I give form to what is ready to live.',
        ),
        (
          totalDay: 5,
          starCluster:
              '✨ msḥtjw ḥꜣt — new life asking nourishment, where birth must be followed by feeding if it is to continue',
          maatPrinciple: 'Feed what has just emerged',
          cosmicContext: '''
What is newly born does not continue by momentum alone.
In Kemet, emergence immediately created new labor. What came into life now required feeding. Time, warmth, order, resource, patience, repetition, and the correct environment had to be given to it. Without that, first appearance became brief appearance.
Day 5 is nourishment.
You ask what this new thing needs immediately if it is to live beyond announcement. Does it need time? Protection? Money? Simplicity? Repetition? Stronger boundaries? Better sleep? More learning? A smaller scope? A cleaner atmosphere?
Birth is not self-sustaining at the start.
It survives because someone feeds it properly.
''',
          glyph: 'New vessel receiving its first offering',
          colorFrequency: 'Warm gold, nourishing green, and red earth',
          mantra: 'I feed what is new so it can continue living.',
        ),
        (
          totalDay: 6,
          starCluster:
              '✨ msḥtjw ḥꜣt — first life under mercy, where what is newborn must not be judged by the standards of what is already seasoned',
          maatPrinciple: 'Stop demanding maturity too early',
          cosmicContext: '''
One of the easiest ways to damage a birth is to judge it like a finished thing.
In Kemet, first stages were treated according to their stage. The keeper did not confuse emergence with completion. Early form had to be respected as early form. Otherwise impatience became cruelty, and something real was crushed beneath standards it had not yet had time to grow into.
Day 6 is mercy under truth.
You stop expecting full weight-bearing from what has only just entered life. This does not mean laziness. It means correct proportion. You honor the beginning as a beginning.
The new thing may be real and still be small.
To measure it rightly is part of caring for it well.
''',
          glyph: 'Small rising disk beneath the full sun line',
          colorFrequency: 'Pale gold, birthing blue, and gentle red',
          mantra: 'I honor the beginning according to its stage.',
        ),
        (
          totalDay: 7,
          starCluster:
              '✨ msḥtjw ḥꜣt — birth-force settling into rhythm, where care must become repeatable if life is to continue',
          maatPrinciple: 'Establish the first rhythm of care',
          cosmicContext: '''
New life survives best when care stops being accidental.
In Kemet, a beginning could not depend on memory, excitement, or good intentions alone. It needed rhythm. The repeated act. The returning hand. The pattern that told the new thing: you will be fed again, checked again, guarded again, given place again.
Day 7 is a rhythm day.
You create the first repeatable sequence that can keep this new life alive. A time of day. A care cycle. A spending rhythm. A training rhythm. A page count. A rest protocol. A family practice. A protective check-in.
This is where birth begins to move toward endurance.
Without rhythm, beginnings remain at the mercy of mood.
''',
          glyph: 'Repeated marks around the new vessel',
          colorFrequency: 'Warm brown, sustaining gold, and steady blue',
          mantra: 'I keep the new life alive by returning to it.',
        ),
        (
          totalDay: 8,
          starCluster:
              '✨ msḥtjw ḥꜣt — new life at the delicate edge, where what is most vulnerable must be reinforced before growth can relax',
          maatPrinciple: 'Strengthen the fragile edge',
          cosmicContext: '''
Every beginning has a weak edge.
It may be confidence. It may be system. It may be money, time, skill, routine, courage, boundaries, or the ability to keep believing in the thing once the first glow cools. Kemet did not wait for fracture to reveal the weak edge. Wise keepers reinforced it early.
Day 8 is precision in protection.
You identify the point at which this birth is most likely to fail and strengthen it. Add support. Simplify. Protect. Train. Clarify. Reduce exposure. Increase repetition. Build the brace now.
The new thing does not need generalized encouragement.
It needs reinforcement at the exact point where it is still easiest to injure.
''',
          glyph: 'Strengthening cord wrapped at the new seam',
          colorFrequency: 'Flint gray, bright gold, and guarded green',
          mantra: 'I strengthen the place where the new life is still tender.',
        ),
        (
          totalDay: 9,
          starCluster:
              '✨ msḥtjw ḥꜣt — birth becoming burden, where emergence now asks for stewardship rather than celebration alone',
          maatPrinciple: 'Accept the work the birth now asks of you',
          cosmicContext: '''
Every true birth becomes labor again.
Once the new thing exists, it begins making claims. It wants time, care, defense, resources, decision, repetition, and the humility to keep serving it without making everything about how exciting its beginning felt. In Kemet, this was understood. Birth did not end effort. It redirected it.
Day 9 is acceptance of stewardship.
You stop treating the new thing as an event and start treating it as a life now entrusted to you. This may mean more discipline than you wanted, more consistency than you expected, more humility than your imagination included.
But this is the dignity of birth.
What comes into life is no longer asking merely to be admired.
It is asking to be cared for.
''',
          glyph: 'New flame placed on the keeper’s palm',
          colorFrequency: 'Red earth, enduring gold, and steady blue',
          mantra: 'I accept the labor that comes with new life.',
        ),
        (
          totalDay: 10,
          starCluster:
              '✨ msḥtjw ḥꜣt — first birth confirmed, closing the first decan with a new life now established enough to be named as real',
          maatPrinciple: 'Confirm that something now lives',
          cosmicContext: '''
The first decan closes with proof of life.
Something has opened, been guarded, named, embodied, fed, measured with mercy, given rhythm, reinforced at its weak edge, and accepted as responsibility. That means the birth is no longer only conceptual. Something now exists in the world that did not exist before.
This is the dignity of Mesut-Ra.
Birth is not proven by intensity of feeling. It is proven by the presence of a new living form — however small — where before there was only hidden preparation. Day 10 is about seeing that clearly.
Not exaggerating it. Not shrinking it. Recognizing it.
A new work. A new order. A new strength. A new standard. A new beginning of speech, body, house, or stewardship. Something lives now.
The next decan will ask how it is carried inwardly. But today, you simply acknowledge the truth: a birth has happened.
''',
          glyph: 'Living flame before the horizon line',
          colorFrequency: 'Dawn gold, red earth, and sealed blue',
          mantra: 'I honor what has now truly entered life.',
        ),
      ],
    );
  }

  static Map<String, KemeticDayInfo> _buildMesutRaIIEntries() {
    const season = '☀️ Shemu – Season of Harvest';
    const month =
        'Mesut-Ra (Mswt-Rꜥ) — the month of births of Ra, where what has been carried, stored, ordered, and prepared now enters emergence, arrival, and first appearance in the light';
    return _buildGeneratedDecanEntries(
      keyPrefix: 'mswtRa',
      decan: 2,
      decanLabel: 'Mesut-Ra II',
      monthLabelForDate: 'Mesut-Ra',
      month: month,
      season: season,
      flowRows: mesutRaOverrideIIFlowRows,
      entries: [
        (
          totalDay: 11,
          starCluster:
              '✨ ḥry-ib msḥtjw ḥꜣt — the birth-forces drawn inward, where what has newly come into life must now be received in the heart, governed inwardly, and protected from being deformed by the keeper’s private disorder',
          maatPrinciple: 'Receive the birth inwardly',
          cosmicContext: '''
The first decan brought something into life.
The second asks what that new life is doing inside you.
In Kemet, birth was never only an outer event. What emerged into the world also began reorganizing the inner chamber of the one responsible for it. A new child, a new role, a new duty, a new power, a new stage of labor — all of these demanded inward rearrangement. Without that, what was born outwardly could be mishandled inwardly.
That is the labor of ḥry-ib msḥtjw ḥꜣt.
This decan turns the birth toward the heart. It asks whether you are inwardly ready for what has emerged. Whether your motives, emotions, fears, private habits, and loyalties can receive the new thing without warping it. Not every birth is ruined from outside. Some are deformed from within by anxiety, impatience, vanity, or hidden refusal.
So Day 11 begins with inward reception.
What has now entered your life — and what must change in you so you can hold it well?
Birth becomes stable when the inner life makes room for what the outer life has just welcomed.
''',
          glyph: 'New flame established in the heart chamber',
          colorFrequency: 'Deep lapis, dawn gold, and living red',
          mantra: 'What has entered life, I now receive inwardly and keep.',
        ),
        (
          totalDay: 12,
          starCluster:
              '✨ ḥry-ib msḥtjw ḥꜣt — inward birth under first tension, where the keeper must recognize fear without letting fear become the first parent of the new thing',
          maatPrinciple: 'Quiet the first fear',
          cosmicContext: '''
Every real birth awakens vulnerability.
Something new now exists, and that means something in you may immediately begin fearing loss, failure, exposure, inadequacy, or the burden of continuity. In Kemet, such fear was not proof the birth was wrong. It was proof that emergence had weight. But fear could not be allowed to rule the chamber.
Day 12 is not denial.
It is naming fear without handing it authority. Maybe you fear not being able to sustain this new phase. Maybe you fear its demands. Maybe you fear other people seeing it. Maybe you fear that it will fail and expose you. Maybe you fear loving it because love would make loss hurt more.
That fear can be acknowledged.
But it cannot be enthroned. What is born should be nourished by care, not raised under the voice of panic.
''',
          glyph: 'Guarding hand behind the new flame',
          colorFrequency: 'Dark blue, soft gold, and guarded red',
          mantra: 'I name my fear, but I do not let it raise what is new.',
        ),
        (
          totalDay: 13,
          starCluster:
              '✨ ḥry-ib msḥtjw ḥꜣt — inward birth becoming obligation, where the keeper must stop treating emergence like a passing event and accept it as a claim',
          maatPrinciple: 'Accept the claim of the new life',
          cosmicContext: '''
A birth is not merely something that happened. It is something that now asks.
This is where many people hesitate. They love the arrival, but resist the claim. They enjoy the hope, but avoid the obligation. In Kemet, that would have been a failure of reception. To welcome a thing into life while refusing what it now requires was a quiet betrayal of emergence.
Day 13 is about honest acceptance.
This new thing — your discipline, work, role, responsibility, healing, order, vow, or restored strength — now has a rightful claim on you. It asks for time, for rearrangement, for protection, for new decisions, for loyalty, for a changed interior line of obedience.
You do not need to dramatize that.
You simply need to stop pretending the birth has no cost.
What is truly welcomed is also truly received as responsibility.
''',
          glyph: 'New vessel set firmly into the keeper’s arms',
          colorFrequency: 'Clay red, gold, and grounded blue',
          mantra: 'What is born now rightfully claims my care.',
        ),
        (
          totalDay: 14,
          starCluster:
              '✨ ḥry-ib msḥtjw ḥꜣt — the birth-force hindered by hesitation, where inward retreat weakens what outwardly has already begun',
          maatPrinciple: 'Stop withholding yourself from the birth',
          cosmicContext: '''
Sometimes the new thing has arrived, but the keeper has not fully come with it.
A person can let something begin and still stand back from it inwardly. He withholds belief. Holds back labor. Keeps a distance in case it fails. Offers partial care so that he will not feel full disappointment. In Kemet, this half-welcome would have weakened the life at its root.
Day 14 is about ending the retreat.
Where are you still keeping your heart, labor, trust, or seriousness one step away from what you asked to be born? Where are you acting as though caution is wisdom when it is really fear wearing a cleaner face?
There is a difference between protection and withdrawal.
A new life needs wise guarding, yes. But it also needs the keeper to come close enough to truly care.
''',
          glyph: 'Two hands closing fully around the new flame',
          colorFrequency: 'Guarded gold, warm red, and deep blue',
          mantra: 'I stop standing back from what I now must truly keep.',
        ),
        (
          totalDay: 15,
          starCluster:
              '✨ ḥry-ib msḥtjw ḥꜣt — the inner birthing chamber requiring clean air, where new life cannot grow well in a poisoned inward atmosphere',
          maatPrinciple: 'Clean the inward climate',
          cosmicContext: '''
A new life can be damaged by the atmosphere around it even when nothing strikes it directly.
Resentment, cynicism, comparison, hidden shame, quiet chaos, habitual self-contempt, and stale inner noise all affect what is trying to grow. In Kemet, chambers were tended not only in form but in condition. What was housed there depended on the climate being kept rightly.
Day 15 is atmospheric correction.
You identify one inward condition that is making the new thing harder to keep alive. Then you begin removing it. Not someday. Now. This may mean confession, cutting off a recurring comparison, ending a private lie, changing what you consume, or refusing the old inner speech that keeps contaminating the new season.
Birth needs more than form.
It needs breathable inward air.
''',
          glyph: 'Window opened in the inner chamber',
          colorFrequency: 'Air blue, dawn gold, and clearing black',
          mantra: 'I clear the inward air so new life can breathe.',
        ),
        (
          totalDay: 16,
          starCluster:
              '✨ ḥry-ib msḥtjw ḥꜣt — birth drawing loyalty from the heart, where care must become more than duty and deepen into inward bond',
          maatPrinciple: 'Attach the heart to the new life',
          cosmicContext: '''
Something changes when care becomes loyalty.
At first a person may tend a new thing because it is necessary. But in Kemet, what was truly received became more than obligation. The heart stood with it. There was bond. Not sentimentality. Not possession. But the inward alignment that says: this life is now under my regard, and I will not treat it casually.
Day 16 asks for that inward bond.
You do not merely perform the labor. You let the heart attach itself rightly. To the discipline. The healing. The work. The standard. The child. The order. The role. The rising thing. What has been born now needs not only management, but loyalty.
The new life grows differently when it is not merely handled, but inwardly held.
''',
          glyph: 'Heart bound by cord to the new flame',
          colorFrequency: 'Deep red, lapis, and steady gold',
          mantra: 'I let my heart stand with what has been born.',
        ),
        (
          totalDay: 17,
          starCluster:
              '✨ ḥry-ib msḥtjw ḥꜣt — the inward birthing chamber exposed to division, where wanting the birth and resisting its labor must finally be reconciled',
          maatPrinciple: 'End the double mind',
          cosmicContext: '''
A divided keeper weakens the newborn life.
One part says yes. Another resists. One part wants the meaning of the new season. Another wants the comfort of the old one. One part celebrates the emergence. Another quietly complains about the cost, the repetition, the discipline, the change in identity it now demands.
Kemet required a cleaner inward line than that.
Day 17 is about ending the split. Not by pretending the labor is easy, but by refusing to keep feeding two loyalties at once. What has been born cannot thrive where its keeper remains inwardly double-minded.
You may still feel the pull backward.
But today you stop building a private room for retreat inside the same house where the birth is trying to grow.
''',
          glyph: 'Single flame where two shadows once stood',
          colorFrequency: 'Black, birthing red, and decisive gold',
          mantra: 'I stop dividing myself against what I must now raise.',
        ),
        (
          totalDay: 18,
          starCluster:
              '✨ ḥry-ib msḥtjw ḥꜣt — inward birth teaching new forms of care, where what has emerged requires a different tenderness than older forms of labor',
          maatPrinciple: 'Learn the new tenderness',
          cosmicContext: '''
Not every good thing is kept by the same touch.
A newborn discipline is not handled like an old craft. A new healing is not treated like a finished strength. A freshly restored trust is not managed like an old habit. In Kemet, different forms of life demanded different kinds of care, and the wise keeper learned the touch required by the stage.
Day 18 is schooling in tenderness.
You let the new thing teach you how it must be handled. More gently? More steadily? More privately? With better timing? With firmer boundaries? With less talking? With more repetition? With less pressure and more attentiveness?
This is not softness for its own sake.
It is precision in care. Tenderness means treating the thing according to what it actually needs in order to live.
''',
          glyph: 'Gentle hand beneath the first flame',
          colorFrequency: 'Soft gold, warm clay, and listening blue',
          mantra: 'I learn the touch this new life actually needs.',
        ),
        (
          totalDay: 19,
          starCluster:
              '✨ ḥry-ib msḥtjw ḥꜣt — inward welcome under trial, where pressure reveals whether the birth has truly been received or is still being endangered by the keeper’s old reflexes',
          maatPrinciple: 'Test the inward welcome',
          cosmicContext: '''
Pressure tells the truth about reception.
A person may say he has welcomed the new thing, but how does he react when pressure arrives? Does he become rough, dismissive, avoidant, chaotic, self-pitying, or careless again? Or does the new inward bond hold even when the day stops being easy?
Kemet trusted trial more than sentiment.
Day 19 is not about catastrophe. It is about honest contact. Under fatigue, interruption, temptation, or inconvenience, does your inward life now protect the birth — or threaten it? Are your private reflexes safer than they were before? Has the atmosphere truly changed?
What is inwardly welcomed should survive first pressure with at least some new steadiness.
If not, the chamber still needs work.
''',
          glyph: 'New flame holding steady in the wind',
          colorFrequency: 'Dark blue, ember red, and proving gold',
          mantra: 'I test whether my inner welcome holds under pressure.',
        ),
        (
          totalDay: 20,
          starCluster:
              '✨ ḥry-ib msḥtjw ḥꜣt — birth established in the inner chamber, closing the second decan with the new life more fully received, claimed, and inwardly protected',
          maatPrinciple: 'Seal the inward adoption',
          cosmicContext: '''
The second decan closes with a more intimate kind of proof.
Something has now been born and not merely observed. It has been received inwardly, defended from fear, accepted as claim, brought closer, protected from poisonous atmosphere, bound to the heart, freed from double-mindedness, handled with more fitting tenderness, and tested under first pressures.
That is the work of ḥry-ib msḥtjw ḥꜣt.
The birth now lives not only in the outer world, but in the inner house. It has a chamber in you. That is what this day seals. Not perfection. Not final maturity. But adoption. The new thing is no longer something you are merely evaluating from the outside. It is something you now mean to keep alive.
So Day 20 is inward claiming.
You name what has now become truly yours to guard, nourish, and carry — and what in you has changed to make that possible.
A birth becomes stronger when the heart finally stops treating it like a visitor.
''',
          glyph: 'Heart seal placed over the living flame',
          colorFrequency: 'Deep lapis, warm gold, and settled red',
          mantra: 'What has been born, I now inwardly claim and keep.',
        ),
      ],
    );
  }

  static Map<String, KemeticDayInfo> _buildMesutRaIIIEntries() {
    const season = '☀️ Shemu – Season of Harvest';
    const month =
        'Mesut-Ra (Mswt-Rꜥ) — the month of births of Ra, where what has been carried, stored, ordered, and prepared now enters emergence, arrival, and first appearance in the light';
    return _buildGeneratedDecanEntries(
      keyPrefix: 'mswtRa',
      decan: 3,
      decanLabel: 'Mesut-Ra III',
      monthLabelForDate: 'Mesut-Ra',
      month: month,
      season: season,
      flowRows: mesutRaOverrideIIIFlowRows,
      entries: [
        (
          totalDay: 21,
          starCluster:
              '✨ sbꜣ msḥtjw ḥꜣt — the guiding star of first births, where what has newly come into life must now become steady enough to orient action, shape conduct, and begin carrying its own light',
          maatPrinciple: 'Let the new life begin to guide',
          cosmicContext: '''
The third decan begins when birth must do more than simply survive.
What has emerged has already been named, embodied, fed, guarded, and inwardly accepted. Now a new question rises: can this new life begin to guide? In Kemet, first appearance was never meant to remain only a fragile event. What was truly born had to enter order strongly enough that the day could start arranging itself around it.
That is the work of sbꜣ msḥtjw ḥꜣt.
This is birth becoming orientation. Not full maturity yet, but enough steadiness that what has come into life can now begin to lead choices, shape rhythm, and correct the old pattern that existed before it. The newborn thing is no longer only asking for protection. It is beginning to ask for place, direction, and influence.
So Day 21 is about rightful guidance.
What has now been born in you strongly enough that it should start setting the line for what comes next? A new discipline. A new honesty. A new role. A restored strength. A cleaner standard. A more truthful devotion. Something no longer belongs only in the nursery of possibility.
It is ready to begin giving light.
''',
          glyph: 'New flame beneath a guiding star',
          colorFrequency: 'Dawn gold, ember red, and deep horizon blue',
          mantra: 'What has been born in truth now begins to guide.',
        ),
        (
          totalDay: 22,
          starCluster:
              '✨ sbꜣ msḥtjw ḥꜣt — first birth beginning to govern its surroundings, where the old day must now make room for the new thing to lead',
          maatPrinciple: 'Rearrange the day around the birth',
          cosmicContext: '''
A birth that changes nothing around it remains too weak.
In Kemet, real emergence altered sequence. Once something new entered life, other things had to move in response. Time shifted. Space shifted. Effort shifted. The old arrangement could not remain untouched if the new thing was truly to live.
Day 22 is about alignment.
You stop acting as though the old order still deserves full command. If a new truth has been born, the schedule must answer it. If a new discipline has emerged, the body and day must honor it. If a new role is real, the surrounding structure must stop pretending otherwise.
New life asks for reordering.
Without that, the old pattern quietly smothers the very thing you claim to welcome.
''',
          glyph: 'New flame set at the front of the day-board',
          colorFrequency: 'Soft gold, black stone, and active red',
          mantra: 'I move the day around what is now alive.',
        ),
        (
          totalDay: 23,
          starCluster:
              '✨ sbꜣ msḥtjw ḥꜣt — new life under guarding light, exposing the force that still tries to cut it off before it strengthens',
          maatPrinciple: 'Remove what is still threatening the birth',
          cosmicContext: '''
A new life does not only need feeding. It needs defense.
In Kemet, what was born into light also entered a world of pressure. Not everything around it was neutral. Some things threatened growth directly: neglect, poor atmosphere, untimely exposure, old habits, hostile speech, careless handling, wasted energy. Wise keepers did not merely hope the new thing would survive. They removed the threat.
Day 23 is a cutting day.
You identify the factor still endangering this new emergence and you deal with it. Not later. Now. One habit, one distraction, one old indulgence, one recurring confusion, one voice of contempt, one leaky structure.
Protection is not passive.
Sometimes the life survives because the keeper finally says: this no longer gets access.
''',
          glyph: 'Blade protecting the new flame',
          colorFrequency: 'Flint gray, ember red, and guarding gold',
          mantra: 'I remove what threatens what is trying to live.',
        ),
        (
          totalDay: 24,
          starCluster:
              '✨ sbꜣ msḥtjw ḥꜣt — birth rising into honorable visibility, where what is now alive must be given a rightful place in the open',
          maatPrinciple: 'Give the birth its place',
          cosmicContext: '''
Something newly born can remain hidden too long.
Protection is necessary, but so is rightful placement. In Kemet, what had survived its first vulnerability had to be set where it belonged in the visible order. Not flaunted. Not paraded. But given its actual place among the duties, rhythms, and structures of life.
Day 24 is about honorable placement.
You stop treating the new thing as an exception or secret side project if it has now grown beyond that stage. Give it room. Give it time. Give it structure. Give it a visible place on the calendar, in the house, in the role, in the budget, in the speech, in the labor.
What is truly alive should no longer be treated like an intruder in its own home.
''',
          glyph: 'New flame set at the front of the chamber',
          colorFrequency: 'Sun gold, polished clay, and steady blue',
          mantra: 'I give rightful place to what has truly come alive.',
        ),
        (
          totalDay: 25,
          starCluster:
              '✨ sbꜣ msḥtjw ḥꜣt — birth becoming legible in conduct, where what has changed within must now begin showing in the outer life',
          maatPrinciple: 'Let your life show the birth',
          cosmicContext: '''
A birth is known by what it changes.
If something has truly come into life, it eventually alters conduct. Speech changes. Pace changes. Choices change. Standards change. Use of time changes. The body begins obeying a different order. In Kemet, the reality of inner transformation could not remain forever invisible. Life around it eventually had to testify.
Day 25 is outward witness.
You let one visible part of your conduct now reflect the birth. More truth in speech. Cleaner sequence. More disciplined rest. Better handling of resources. A firmer boundary. A truer pace. A different answer under pressure.
The point is not performance.
It is congruence. What has truly been born inside you should no longer leave the outer life unchanged.
''',
          glyph: 'New rising disk mirrored in the walking figure',
          colorFrequency: 'Bright gold, warm red, and living blue',
          mantra: 'I let the birth be seen in how I live.',
        ),
        (
          totalDay: 26,
          starCluster:
              '✨ sbꜣ msḥtjw ḥꜣt — new life strengthened into rule, where what has been born must now be secured against forgetting and decline',
          maatPrinciple: 'Strengthen the new order',
          cosmicContext: '''
Birth without reinforcement fades into memory.
Kemet understood that first life had to become repeated life if it was to endure. What had newly emerged needed law, rhythm, structure, and reinforcement, or the old order would slowly absorb it back into itself.
Day 26 is a strengthening day.
You reinforce the habit, system, vow, or structure that will keep this birth from dissolving. Add repetition. Build the support. Write the rule. Simplify the pathway. Protect the time. Deepen the chamber. Remove the ambiguity.
New life becomes a new order when it stops depending on momentary fire and starts being secured by form.
What is born now must be given a way to remain.
''',
          glyph: 'Rising disk fastened to the horizon line',
          colorFrequency: 'Dawn gold, fixed blue, and strengthening red',
          mantra: 'I give the new life the structure it needs to remain.',
        ),
        (
          totalDay: 27,
          starCluster:
              '✨ sbꜣ msḥtjw ḥꜣt — birth becoming transmissible, where what has newly come alive must now begin changing the order around it',
          maatPrinciple: 'Let the new life teach the field',
          cosmicContext: '''
A true birth does not remain isolated.
In Kemet, what rose rightly eventually affected more than the one who held it. New order began influencing the house, the labor, the speech, the atmosphere, the sequence of actions, and the expectations of those nearby. Life teaches by presence once it becomes stable enough.
Day 27 is outward effect.
You let the birth begin instructing the field around it. Maybe through example. Maybe through a cleaner standard. Maybe through a better process. Maybe by sharing what you have learned. Maybe by altering how the room moves because something in you is no longer negotiable.
The new thing does not need to dominate.
It simply needs to be alive enough that others can now feel its order.
What is born in truth begins to radiate.
''',
          glyph: 'New flame casting order across the room',
          colorFrequency: 'Living gold, chamber blue, and warm red',
          mantra: 'What is born in me now begins to teach by how it lives.',
        ),
        (
          totalDay: 28,
          starCluster:
              '✨ sbꜣ msḥtjw ḥꜣt — living birth under guard, where the old order still seeks re-entry if the threshold is left unkept',
          maatPrinciple: 'Refuse the return of what once ruled',
          cosmicContext: '''
Every new life has an old world trying to reclaim the chamber.
The old habit still knows the path. The old fear still knows the argument. The old indulgence still knows the hour of weakness. The old disorder still waits for the day you are tired enough to stop guarding the threshold. In Kemet, what was newly born had to be defended from return pressures, not only from first dangers.
Day 28 is threshold defense.
You identify what old pattern is still trying to move back in and take up space against the birth. Then you stop it. Not emotionally. Cleanly. The old schedule. The old appetite. The old speech. The old self-story. The old compromise.
What is new survives not only by growth, but by firm refusal of what would quietly reclaim the room.
''',
          glyph: 'Threshold barred behind the living flame',
          colorFrequency: 'Black stone, ember red, and defending gold',
          mantra: 'I guard the birth from the return of what it replaced.',
        ),
        (
          totalDay: 29,
          starCluster:
              '✨ sbꜣ msḥtjw ḥꜣt — living birth under review, where the keeper must separate what has truly taken root from what merely felt intense for a moment',
          maatPrinciple: 'Confirm what is truly alive',
          cosmicContext: '''
Not every bright beginning survives long enough to become life.
That is why Kemet returned to review. What has truly taken root? What now repeats? What now changes the order? What now holds under use? What now asks real care because it is undeniably present? And what was only heat, emotion, projection, or the wish for a new identity without the labor of carrying it?
Day 29 is sober confirmation.
You look honestly at what is alive now. Not what sounded beautiful. Not what you hoped to be true by now. What is actually living — in your body, schedule, labor, conduct, stewardship, or devotion.
Truth here is not discouragement.
It is protection of the real. What truly lives deserves different treatment than what merely flared and vanished.
''',
          glyph: 'Living flame measured against the horizon',
          colorFrequency: 'Horizon blue, bright gold, and truth-red',
          mantra: 'I distinguish what truly lives from what only flared.',
        ),
        (
          totalDay: 30,
          starCluster:
              '✨ sbꜣ msḥtjw ḥꜣt — the guiding star of first births sealed in purpose, closing the month with a life now emerged, inwardly received, outwardly guarded, and ready to continue under Ma’at',
          maatPrinciple: 'Dedicate the birth to lasting purpose',
          cosmicContext: '''
Mesut-Ra closes not with mere arrival, but with consecration.
What was hidden has emerged. What emerged has been named, given body, fed, protected, accepted inwardly, brought into conduct, strengthened, defended from return, and confirmed as real. That is the full labor of birth in Kemet. Not sentiment. Not sudden magic. Ordered emergence into life.
That is the completion of sbꜣ msḥtjw ḥꜣt.
The birth now asks its final first question: what is it for? What service will it render? What order will it strengthen? What continuity will it enter? What pattern of Ma’at will it now be asked to serve beyond your excitement, beyond your self-image, beyond the raw thrill of something new?
So Day 30 is dedication.
You place this new life under purpose, discipline, and right relation. Because a birth that is not dedicated is still vulnerable to drift. But a birth given to worthy use gains direction, endurance, and deeper legitimacy.
What has entered life now needs a reason to remain.
''',
          glyph: 'New flame offered before the horizon of Ra',
          colorFrequency: 'Dawn gold, deep red, and consecrated blue',
          mantra: 'What has been born in truth, I dedicate to lasting order.',
        ),
      ],
    );
  }

  static Map<String, KemeticDayInfo> _buildHeriuRenpetEntries() {
    const season = '☀️ Shemu – Season of Harvest';
    const month =
        'Heriu Renpet (ḥr.w rnpt) — the Five Days Upon the Year, the sacred threshold where the old cycle empties and the divine births open the way for renewal';
    return Map.fromEntries([
      _dayInfoEntry(
        key: 'epagomenal_1_1',
        kemeticDate: 'Heriu Renpet, Day 1',
        season: season,
        month: month,
        decanName:
            'Wesir (Wsir) — Birth of Endurance, Restoration, and Right Continuity',
        starCluster:
            '✨ The first day of the year’s threshold opens with continuity reclaimed — what was broken, buried, or scattered is called back into living order',
        maatPrinciple: 'Restore what must continue',
        cosmicContext: '''
Heriu Renpet begins at the edge of endings.
The harvest has already done its work. What could ripen has ripened. What could be gathered has been gathered. Now the year pauses outside ordinary sequence. These are not regular calendar days. They are threshold days — charged, exposed, and close to the powers that govern birth, death, continuity, and return.
Day 1 belongs to Wesir.
This is not merely a day of grief or memory. It is a day of reassembly. In Kemet, Wesir represents what can be cut down and still return in another form. Not through fantasy, but through law: what is true, rightly ordered, and joined to the eternal pattern can be restored.
So today you look at what in your life must not be left in fragments.
A discipline. A vow. A piece of dignity. A sacred routine. A relationship with the divine. A part of yourself that has been neglected, but not destroyed.
The first work of the threshold is not novelty.
It is rightful restoration.
''',
        decanFlow: heriuRenpetOverrideFlowRows,
        meduNeter: MeduNeterKey(
          glyph: 'Djed rising from reassembled earth',
          colorFrequency: 'Dark earth, enduring green, and threshold gold',
          mantra: 'I restore what must continue.',
        ),
      ),
      _dayInfoEntry(
        key: 'epagomenal_2_1',
        kemeticDate: 'Heriu Renpet, Day 2',
        season: season,
        month: month,
        decanName:
            'Heru-Wer (Ḥr-wr) — Birth of Right Vision, Upright Rule, and Clear Ascent',
        starCluster:
            '✨ The second threshold day brings height, sight, and rightful perspective — the power to stand above confusion and see what must be governed',
        maatPrinciple: 'Raise your sightline',
        cosmicContext: '''
Once continuity is restored, vision must return.
A person can recover strength and still remain directionless. He can rebuild order and still keep his eyes too low, fixed on noise, reaction, appetite, and small confusion. Day 2 interrupts that. Heru-Wer lifts the line of sight.
In Kemet, this is the force that rises above entanglement without leaving responsibility behind.
Not escape. Not detachment for its own sake. Clear vantage.
So today is about elevation of perception.
What are you looking at too closely? What has become bigger in your mind than it deserves? What would change if you stopped staring at the dust and looked again at the full pattern of your life, your role, your house, your work, and your duty?
The second threshold day asks you to see from above without becoming arrogant.
Right rule begins with right sight.
''',
        decanFlow: heriuRenpetOverrideFlowRows,
        meduNeter: MeduNeterKey(
          glyph: 'Falcon eye raised above the horizon',
          colorFrequency: 'Sky blue, sun gold, and clean black',
          mantra: 'I lift my sight to govern rightly.',
        ),
      ),
      _dayInfoEntry(
        key: 'epagomenal_3_1',
        kemeticDate: 'Heriu Renpet, Day 3',
        season: season,
        month: month,
        decanName:
            'Sutekh (Stẖ) — Birth of Force, Fracture, Trial, and Necessary Disruption',
        starCluster:
            '✨ The third threshold day reveals raw force — not evil by itself, but dangerous when unguided and powerful when harnessed to boundary, courage, and exact correction',
        maatPrinciple: 'Harness the dangerous force',
        cosmicContext: '''
Not everything sacred feels gentle.
The threshold does not only birth restoration and vision. It also births force — the untamed current that can either shatter order or help defend it. Sutekh belongs to storms, pressure, hostility, conflict, interruption, and the energy that does not naturally move in harmony unless brought under law.
This is why Day 3 must be handled with honesty.
Somewhere in you there is force that has not been fully yoked: anger, ambition, hunger, defiance, will, sexual charge, survival instinct, appetite for dominance, appetite for escape. Pretending it is not there does not purify it. It only sends it underground.
So today is not about becoming softer than truth.
It is about becoming strong enough to govern what is dangerous in you before it governs you.
A threshold worthy of Ma’at does not deny chaos.
It puts a boundary around it and makes it answer.
''',
        decanFlow: heriuRenpetOverrideFlowRows,
        meduNeter: MeduNeterKey(
          glyph: 'Set-standard before a marked boundary line',
          colorFrequency: 'Storm red, black stone, and desert gold',
          mantra: 'I govern the force before it governs me.',
        ),
      ),
      _dayInfoEntry(
        key: 'epagomenal_4_1',
        kemeticDate: 'Heriu Renpet, Day 4',
        season: season,
        month: month,
        decanName:
            'Aset (ꜣst) — Birth of Deep Intelligence, Protection, Naming, and Sacred Gathering',
        starCluster:
            '✨ The fourth threshold day gathers scattered power through wisdom — the force that names correctly, protects precisely, and restores hidden coherence',
        maatPrinciple: 'Gather through wisdom',
        cosmicContext: '''
After force, intelligence must return.
Aset is not merely softness, devotion, or mystery. She is disciplined sacred intelligence — the ability to gather what has been broken, to perceive what others miss, to protect what is vulnerable, and to use right naming as a form of power.
Day 4 belongs to the mind that heals through precision.
Not overtalking. Not panic. Not rushing. Wisdom.
So today asks: what needs to be gathered back together through careful intelligence rather than raw effort? A plan. A family rhythm. A spiritual practice. A budget. A wounded conversation. A scattered self.
Aset does not waste motion.
She studies, names, collects, shields, and restores.
This threshold day reminds you that not every problem is solved by pushing harder.
Some are solved by seeing more deeply and handling more carefully.
''',
        decanFlow: heriuRenpetOverrideFlowRows,
        meduNeter: MeduNeterKey(
          glyph: 'Tjet knot gathered in two careful hands',
          colorFrequency: 'Milk white, red cord, and midnight blue',
          mantra: 'I gather through wisdom, not panic.',
        ),
      ),
      _dayInfoEntry(
        key: 'epagomenal_5_1',
        kemeticDate: 'Heriu Renpet, Day 5',
        season: season,
        month: month,
        decanName:
            'Nebet-Het (Nb.t-ḥt) — Birth of Threshold Guarding, Hidden Support, Mourning, and Sacred Closure',
        starCluster:
            '✨ The fifth threshold day watches the edge itself — the hidden hand that tends endings correctly, accompanies what must be released, and guards the crossing into the next cycle',
        maatPrinciple: 'Close the year with clean hands',
        cosmicContext: '''
The last threshold day belongs to the keeper of edges.
Nebet-Het stands where the visible world thins out — at endings, funerary spaces, hidden support, private sorrow, and the quiet labor of closing what must be closed without spectacle. She is often near what others avoid looking at: grief, exhaustion, aftermath, and the silent work of attending what is passing out of one form into another.
That makes Day 5 a day of clean closure.
Not denial. Not collapse. Not dragging unfinished residue into the next cycle because you lacked the courage to end something properly.
So today you ask: what must be closed with reverence? What must be mourned without becoming your identity? What must be laid down, thanked, sealed, buried, recorded, or released so the new year does not inherit unnecessary decay?
Nebet-Het teaches that thresholds are not crossed well by pretending nothing is ending.
They are crossed well by honoring the ending and guarding the passage.
The five days close here.
What enters the new year should do so through a clean threshold.
''',
        decanFlow: heriuRenpetOverrideFlowRows,
        meduNeter: MeduNeterKey(
          glyph: 'Veiled lamp at the threshold',
          colorFrequency: 'Indigo dusk, silver ash, and quiet gold',
          mantra: 'I close the year with clean hands.',
        ),
      ),
    ]);
  }

